<F P=100> Ecuador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Strike To Protest Government Privatization Program </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Strike To Protest Government Privatization Program </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2704011894 Hamburg DPA in Spanish 1426 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2704011894 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Quito, 26 Apr (DPA) -- At least 40 public sector 
union organizations decided to go on a 48-hour strike on Tuesday 
to protest the privatization program of the Liberal 
administration headed by Sixto Duran-Ballen. The strike 
coincides with the closing stages of the campaign by provincial 
deputies, advisers, and councilmen seeking reelection in the 1 
May elections. 
  The unions expressed their opposition to the privatization 
program in general and in particular as it relates to so-called 
strategic sectors such as petroleum, electricity, and 
telecommunications. 
  Recent announcements related to electricity cuts and fuel 
interruptions have not yet materialized, but the government has 
announced through Carlos Larreategui, secretary general of the 
administration, that it could take a tough stance against the 
union leaders, warning that it could even put them on trial. 
  In the meantime, the Education Ministry suspended classes at 
all schools and universities throughout when teacher joined the 
48-hour strike. Indian groups also decided to support the unions 
and threatened to block all highways to keep "Ecuador from being 
auctioned off to foreign interests." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

