Daily Report 
<DATE1>  26 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mexican Granma Expedition Member Buried in Havana </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mexican Granma Expedition Member Buried in Havana </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL2604145594 Havana Tele Rebelde and Cuba Vision Networks in 
Spanish 0000 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2604145594 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Tele Rebelde and Cuba Vision Networks </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Since it was his wish to be buried in Cuba, 
outstanding revolutionary Alfonso Guillen Zelaya was buried at 
the Colon Cemetery today. Commander of the Revolution Juan 
Almeida Bosque, along with relatives, friends and 
comrades-in-arms, headed the procession, and funeral. 
  Alfonso Guillen Zelaya's rich past was recalled today by his 
comrade, Gabriel Gil Alfonso. Guillen Zelaya was the youngest 
member of the Granma expedition. He was arrested after his 
active participation in the Alegria de Pio affair. To the 
prosecutor who tried him, Guillen said: One need not be Cuban to 
fight for liberty, for all men of justice fight for liberty 
wherever it may be offended. 
  Because of his firmness, in 1957 he was deported to Mexico 
where, directed by the 26 July movement, which was in exile, he 
carried out important missions. With the triumph of the 
Revolution, Guillen returned to Cuba, where he held different 
administrative positions. He was vice president of the Cuban 
Institute of Friendship with Peoples for 10 years. 
  As an education ministry official, he attended the Latin 
American and Caribbean Congress of Teachers in Mexico, where he 
was surprised by death at the age of 57. Guillen received 
numerous decorations and distinctions, among them the award for 
being one of the founders of the Communist Party of Cuba. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

