<H3> <TI>   Trotskyist Electoral Alliance Disbanded </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Trotskyist Electoral Alliance Disbanded </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2804143294 Buenos Aires PAGINA/12 in Spanish 27 Apr 94 p 6 </F>
<F P=103> PY2804143294 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires PAGINA/12 </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] "The Socialist Left Front [FIS] electoral 
alliance was disbanded on 10 April. We will continue to work 
together on the agreed tasks, but as a front, it is disbanded." 
With these words, a spokeswoman of the Movement Toward 
Socialism (MAS) signed the death certificate for the front that 
groups Trotskyist leaning parties. The other two groups that 
made up the front -- the Socialist Movement of the Workers 
(MST), headed by Luis Zamora, and the Workers Party (PO), headed 
by Jorge Altamirano -- have decided to act jointly. As a first 
measure, on 1 May at 1500 there will be a commemoration of Labor 
Day at the Plaza de Mayo. The MAS will hold its own 
commemoration at the Boxing Federation. [passage omitted] 
  Thus, the Trotskyist alliance ends following its poor 
performance in the 10 April elections. It had been born in 
February. At the national level, the Trotskyists lost 31,000 
votes compared with the results they obtained in October 1993, 
with a large loss in the Federal Capital and especially in 
Greater Buenos Aires. In these two districts "the wave rolled 
toward the Grand Front and we could do nothing," a spokesperson 
acknowledged on 26 April, "but in the provinces of Jujuy, 
Neuquen, Salta, Santiago del Estero, and especially in Santa 
Cruz we increased our vote. There were workers' struggles in 
those provinces and it is no coincidence that we had better 
results there." In Santa Cruz Province the FIS obtained two 
seats in the Constituent Assembly, the only seats that it was 
able to gain in the whole country. 

</TEXT>

