<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Congress President on Suspension </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Congress President on Suspension </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2904034294 Guatemala City Teleonce Television in Spanish 
0400 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2904034294 </F>
<F P=104>  Guatemala City Teleonce Television </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Telepress" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The Constitutionality Court will have to decide 
whether it will process the appeal filed by the Supreme 
Electoral Tribunal against the temporary suspension of the 
election for new deputies. This issue aroused various reactions 
on Monday in judicial and political circles. National Congress 
President Vinicio Villar Anleu commented on the implications of 
the case: 
  [Begin recording] [Villar Anleu] It seems to us -- and we 
uphold Congress' institutional policy -- that the nation's laws 
must be respected and that the Constitution must be respected. 
In this case, we will obey any legal decision issued. What is 
interesting is that we are not only operating under a democratic 
process with a government that is respecting the Constitution, 
but we are also operating under a de jure state in which the 
decisions of various judicial institutions should prevail -- in 
other words, the decisions of the relevant courts. 
  In this case, a court issued a temporary amparo, and, 
because 
we live in a de jure state, we must obey it. This is a 
temporary amparo. A deeper analysis of the case must be made 
before a definite decision is handed down. The Congress, as an 
institution and as one of the three state branches, is willing 
to respect and always obey the legal opinions handed down by any 
court that has jurisdiction. 
  [Unidentified reporter] What is your opinion about the paid 
advertisement by Alvaro Arzu, one of the secretaries of the 
National Vanguard Party [PAN], who points out that the 
corruption in Congress and... 
  [Second unidentified reporter, interrupting] Saying it is 
responsible for the whole crisis... 
  [Villar Anleu, interrupting] I say what I have always said: 
We respect the opinion of any Guatemalan citizen. In this 
case, Mr. Alvaro Arzu, a citizen like any other, is expressing 
his opinion. This opinion must be respected. As president of 
the Congress, I do not share his opinion. I want to make it 
clear that the deputies were elected by the people during clean, 
democratic, completely legal, and crystal clear elections for a 
five-year term. This term is mandated by the Constitution. 
  As I have said before, in the spirit of helping this 
Congress, we have accepted -- after an agreement with the 
executive -- moving up the legislative elections. Nevertheless, 
the mandate was for five years, and in this case it was the 
people who elected us. If he says there has been 
irresponsibility on the part of the deputies, I would say it is 
the responsibility of all, including the deputies of his party 
-- that is, the PAN -- who resigned last year. They are also 
responsible for any political activity taking place in the 
nation. Therefore, I am sorry he has made these statements. I 
do not share his opinion, but I respect it. That is his 
opinion, and it must be respected. Well, when someone has money 
to spend, he can publish paid advertisements. 
  We, as an institution, respect everyone's opinion, even if 
we 
do not share it. We want to make very clear our position that 
we are complying with a mandate for the upcoming elections. We 
will respect the agreement made with the executive; however, we 
also respect the law and the Constitution. If a court issues a 
decision, we will obey it because we live in a de jure state. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

