<H3> <TI>   Denies Reports of Army `Insubordination' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Denies Reports of Army `Insubordination' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2904025494 Tegucigalpa Telesistema Hondureno Television 
Network in Spanish 0100 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2904025494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tegucigalpa Telesistema Hondureno Television 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Glenda Moreno; from the "This Very Day" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The apparent confrontation between the civilian and 
military sector, generated by the proposal to have a volunteer 
educational, social, humanistic, and democratic military service 
by President Reina, and the dissenting remarks by Defense 
Minister Reinaldo Andino Flores, monopolized the news conference 
the president held today. 
  [Begin Reina recording] Every person interprets the matter 
based on this opinion. What does he mean? That he abides by 
it. He has a different opinion because he does not think the 
volunteer service can meet the needs. Some tried to say he was 
defying this decision. I feel this is not a proper 
interpretation. [end recording] 
  Throughout the news conference, Reina denied there was any 
insubordination on the part of Gen. Andino Flores. 
  [Begin recording] [Reina] Absolutely. How can that be 
insubordination, when he obeys the orders of his boss? 
  [Reporter] [Question indistinct] 
  [Reina] The president is the chief of the Honduran Armed 
Forces. [end recording] 
  What is important, the president said, is that the Executive 
Branch's bill was submitted today to the National Congress. The 
Legislative Branch will have to decide, he said, whether or not 
we are wrong. 
  [Begin Reina recording] I am not afraid of being wrong, 
because this goes to the National Congress, and it will debate 
it. One supposes that all the people are there. If the 
Congress rejects it, I will openly admit I was wrong. [end 
recording] 
  Although the topic of the volunteer, education, social, 
humanistic, and democratic military service monopolized the 
attention of the media, President Reina commented on other 
topics, such as the energy crisis. 
  [Begin Reina recording] Let me tell you that yesterday I 
spoke with the Mexican president. He offered us all his help, 
and if this works out we will overcome the crisis in a few days. 
He is offering two plants that generate 30 megawatts each. We 
will overcome the problem with those 60 megawatts. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

