<F P=100> Bolivia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Military Troops Prevent Oruro Blockades </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Military Troops Prevent Oruro Blockades </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2904150394 La Paz Radio Fides Network in Spanish 1100 GMT 
29 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY2904150394 </F>
<F P=104>  La Paz Radio Fides Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Felix Salazar in Oruro] </F>
  [Text] Heavily armed military troops have prevented several 
attempts by peasants and rural teachers to block roads. Traffic 
on the Oruro-La Paz road was maintained although the flow 
dropped considerably because bus drivers suspended services to 
safeguard their buses. 
  In Caracollo, 37 km from Oruro, peasants and students were 
prevented from blocking the road toward the south. After being 
briefly blocked, a military presence now guarantees the free 
flow of traffic. 
  Peasants blocked the Oruro-Cochabamba road, suspending all 
traffic. The traffic police have reported that the peasants 
broke the windshields of three buses and demanded money to let 
them pass. It has been announced that inter-department bus 
services will be totally normalized today. 
  While there was military presence on the roads yesterday, 
the 
situation in the cities was totally calm, contrary to previous 
days when many demonstrations were held. 
  Railway services are working normally but under military 
custody. Yesterday peasants had to lift their blockade in 
Banderani and Cona Cona stations on the Oruro-Cochabamba railway 
stretch due to the presence of military troops. 
  The national railway service operations manager reported 
that 
services are being provided normally, although every train is 
guarded by military troops. 
  Private school classes were suspended today for 24-hours as 
determined by the Private School Teachers Association in support 
for the urban teachers' demands. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

