<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Stricter Rules for Origin Certificates Proposed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Stricter Rules for Origin Certificates Proposed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2804133894 Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL in Portuguese 26 Apr 
94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> PY2804133894 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Cynthia Malta] </F>
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] Brazil is proposing to its 
Common Market of the South [Mercosur] partners -- Argentina, 
Paraguay, and Uruguay -- the establishment of stricter rules for 
certificates of origin. These rules would go into effect in 
1995, by which time the four countries will be exchanging 
products without charging customs fees. The current rules 
contemplate a minimum national content of 50 percent in each 
product, with the possibility that the tariff may be changed. 
Ambassador Paulo Nogueira Batista, the Brazilian representative 
before the Latin American Integration Association [ALADI] in 
Montevideo, has said that Brazil proposes increasing this 
percentage to 75 percent and demands that product 
classifications be modified. He said that if it is not possible 
to enforce stricter rules, the trade of vehicles within the 
Mercosur would continue via import quotas, even after January 
1995. 
  The Brazilian Government may begin to negotiate a bilateral 
free trade agreement for the implementation of the South 
American Free Trade Area [SAFTA] without affecting its trade 
within Mercosur. Ambassador Nogueira Batista pointed out that 
the Asuncion Treaty, which created the Mercosur, allows this 
initiative. Interested countries can present exception lists on 
which certain products would be protected by higher tariffs. 
The remaining products would have zero tariffs for 10 years as 
of January 1995. Jorge Campbell, Argentine secretary for 
international economic relations, has reservations about the 
negotiation of accords to create SAFTA. He said: "The countries 
that negotiate these accords will have access to an agreement 
which took us a long time to negotiate." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

