<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Reports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2804165194 </F>
<F P=103> PY2804165194 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities monitored through 28 April: 
  Telebras, Brazilian Telecommunications, Inc., has opened the 
social capital of its state subsidiaries expecting to make $260 
million this year. This was announced yesterday when the 
company announced its 1993 balance which showed a $1.143 billion 
net profit. (Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 21 
Apr 93 p B7) 
  Yesterday, the government reduced the import duty on 17 
products to 2 percent. Economic Policy Secretary Winston 
Fritsch said the objective is to warn national industry from 
committing price abuses. The products are soluble coffee; soft 
drinks; beer; cheese and milk byproducts; sugar; tire tubes for 
cars and trucks; tires for cars, trucks, and tractors; car 
generators and dynamos; disc plows; lampblack; ceramic bathroom 
parts; shaving machines; shaving cream; razor blades; oil; 
olives; and seeds and plants. Import duty on aluminum cans and 
condoms were reduced to zero. (Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL in 
Portuguese 21 Apr 94) 
  Central Bank net dollar purchases totaled $1.7 billion in 
March, while international cash reserves grew by $1.4 billion in 
February, to reach $30.5 billion. At the end of January, cash 
reserves stood at $29.1 billion. Liquid reserves, which include 
medium and long-term credits, delayed credits, and provisions 
for the return of capital, stood at $36.5 billion at the end of 
February, while at the end of January they stood at $35.4 
billion. The Central Bank bulletin states that the slower 
reserve growth compared to January, when reserves grew by $3.2 
billion, was caused by a drop in the exchange operations surplus 
registered in February. (Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO in 
Portuguese 22 Apr 94 p B6) 
  German enterprises control 1,027 enterprises in Brazil. This 
is equivalent to 12 percent of the 8,567 foreign capital 
enterprises registered in Brazil. Germans control 65, 47, and 
35 percent, respectively, of the car parts, vehicle, and 
medicine sectors. (Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 
23 Apr 94 p B2) 
  Yesterday, Citibank Senior Vice President Alcides Amaral 
said 
Brazil is again being granted short-term credits. He estimated 
that so far the country has obtained short-term credits worth 
$16 billion, especially for financing exports. The flow of 
short-term credits increased after Brazil began to negotiate its 
foreign debt. In connection with Brazil's debt to private banks, 
on the day the debt negotiation was concluded, the country 
received $352 million. Of this, Citibank provided $220 million. 
(Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 27 Apr 94 p B7) 

</TEXT>

