<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tourism Minister Denies Contact With Israelis </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tourism Minister Denies Contact With Israelis </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN2403155594 Amman AL-SABIL in Arabic 23-28 Mar 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> JN2403155594 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman AL-SABIL </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Majid al-Khudari and Ra'id al-Najjar] </F>
  [Text] The International Tourism Fair was held in Berlin 
last month. In its noon newscast on Monday, 7 March 1994, 
Israel radio said Jordanian Tourism Minister Muhammad al-'Adwan 
visited the Israeli pavilion and made a statement in which he 
said: I hope Jordan and Israel will overcome their extremists 
so the desired peace between the two countries will be realized 
soon. I also hope that after signing a peace agreement between 
the two countries, it will become possible to carry out joint 
tourist projects to attract foreign tourists to Israel and 
Jordan. He said Jordanian businessmen and investors are ready 
to cooperate with their Israeli counterparts on setting up joint 
ventures that serve bilateral economic and tourist interests. 
  Israel radio attributed this statement to al-'Adwan during a 
surprise visit to the Israeli pavilion, as the radio claimed. 
The radio said the Jordanian minister arrived in the pavilion 
unexpectedly, and that the director general of the Israeli 
Ministry of Tourism was quickly called in to receive the 
unexpected guest. 
  Sources at the Israeli pavilion expressed a belief that the 
political relaxation in Middle East relations have a direct 
impact on the change in the Arab world and the visits to various 
Israeli fairs by Arab officials. The Israeli side proposed 
tourist deals to their Arab visitors. 
  Israeli tourists toured Arab pavilions. The director general 
of the Israeli airlines company visited the Yemen pavilion and 
met with Yemeni businessmen. 
  Ahmad al-Ma'ni, director general of a tourist company in 
Dubai, told Israeli press representatives who visited the Dubai 
pavilion that what happened in Hebron turned things upside down. 
  Ibrahim Yasin, a ranking Syrian Tourism Ministry official 
said several Syrian officials are impatiently waiting for the 
time when they will be allowed to visit Israel. 
  In an exclusive statement to AL-SABIL, Dr. Muhammad 
al-'Adwan, Jordanian minister of tourism and antiquities, said 
this report is baseless. He said: I did not visit the Israeli 
pavilion, nor did any member of the Jordanian delegation. No 
one made a statement to the Israeli media. This report is 
totally untrue, he said. 
  He said the objective of Israel radio is to stir up a clamor 
and to try to harm the firm Jordanian position by diverting 
attention from the ugly massacre committed by Israeli settlers. 
  Al-'Adwan welcomed cooperation between AL-SABIL and the 
Ministry of Tourism in the service of the public interest. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-11644 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes062_m_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-062 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  31 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Daily on U.S. `Seige' of al-'Aqabah Port </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Daily on U.S. `Seige' of al-'Aqabah Port </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN3103082994 Amman SAWT AL-SHA'B in Arabic 31 Mar 94 pp 1, 18 </F>
<F P=103> JN3103082994 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman SAWT AL-SHA'B </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Editorial: "Jordan Is Committed to Comprehensive Peace"] </F>
  [Text] Jordan responded to the U.S. call to take part in 
the Madrid conference because the conference was based on 
achieving a comprehensive, just, and lasting peace in accordance 
with the resolutions of international legitimacy and the 
land-for-peace principle. The conference was also based on 
restoring all the occupied Arab territories, foremost of which 
is holy Jerusalem, and on fully restoring the national rights of 
the Palestinian people. 
  However, the U.S. Administration abandoned its role as a 
full 
and effective partner in the peace process and forgot about the 
Madrid terms of reference. It began to encourage and support 
Israel in its attempts to fragment the peace process and to 
strike separate deals. It also gave Israel the liberty to 
maneuver and prevaricate. It went on to plant obstacles on the 
road to a just and comprehensive peace. The U.S. Administration 
bypassed UN Security Council resolutions and tried to impose its 
conditions on the Palestinian and other Arab parties. 
  Furthermore, the U.S. Administration harshly pressured all 
the Arab parties in order to impose Israeli conditions on them. 
As a result, Israel succeeded in imposing the Oslo, Davos, and 
Cairo accords on the Palestinian side. 
  Because Jordan is firmly committed to a just and 
comprehensive peace based on Resolutions 242 and 338, the U.S. 
Administration, at Israel's request, strongly pressured and 
harassed Jordan to agree to sign a separate agreement with 
Israel. The U.S. siege imposed on the Port of al-'Aqabah is 
part of this harassment, which has caused serious harm to 
Jordan's economy and trade. 
  When His Majesty King Husayn visited the United States, he 
was asked to sign a separate peace agreement with Israel before 
the problems of water, occupied territories, and refugees are 
solved. 
  However, His Majesty King Husayn, who has never submitted to 
pressure or harassment from any party, rejected the U.S. offer 
with courage, pride, and a firm Hashemite will. He stressed the 
need to restore Jordanian rights to the occupied territories and 
to the plundered waters, and the need to resolve the issue of 
refugees and evacuees. This spurred a U.S. desire to take 
revenge on Jordan. 
  As a result of all this, the U.S. Administration began to 
tighten the siege on Jordan in order to cause more harm to it. 
Hence, the brave Hashemite response announced by His Majesty 
King Husayn when he linked continuation of Jordan's 
participation in the peace process with the lifting of the siege 
imposed on the Port of al-'Aqabah. He stressed that Jordan is a 
difficult number in the equation and that it will not submit to 
pressures that are suspect in terms of causes and objectives. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

