<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Column Notes Iraqi Press Criticism of Foreign Ministry </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Column Notes Iraqi Press Criticism of Foreign Ministry </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN2603165294 Amman AL-DUSTUR in Arabic 26 Mar 94 pp 36, 32 </F>
<F P=103> JN2603165294 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman AL-DUSTUR </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Last Station" column by Salih al-Qallab: "BABIL's </F>
Admonitions"] 
  [Text] For the second time in less than two months, the 
Iraqi daily BABIL, whose board chairman is 'Udayy Saddam Husayn, 
has criticized Iraq's foreign policy, contending that 
decisionmakers "have given the United Nations and the West 
everything but got nothing in return." 
  Aware that the Iraqi press is state-controlled, foreign 
observers are speculating that BABIL's admonitions may signal an 
imminent shakeup in the Iraqi diplomatic community that may see 
the country's Deputy Prime Minister Tariq 'Aziz and Foreign 
Minister Muhammad Sa'id al-Sahhaf lose their jobs. 
  BABIL's views and commentaries are not necessarily those of 
the decisionmakers in Iraq. It must be pointed out, however, 
that Iraq's foreign policy, and that of all nations, for that 
matter, is a reflection of its internal politics, all the more 
so in the absence of a pluralistic political system of 
government or a state within a state. 
  Out of our concern for Iraq, we will venture to say that 
BABIL's criticisms are not well founded. It does not make sense 
to single out one party for criticism and lay the blame for the 
failure to get the sanctions lifted at the doorstep of Iraq's 
foreign policy makers. It is not so much the preformance of 
this or that Iraqi diplomat that will get the job done. It has 
more to do with Iraq's overall policies, administered by a 
well-known leader. 
  To be fair, there is much to be said for the way the 
diplomatic team led by Tariq 'Aziz conducted itself at the 
height of the Kuwait crisis. Even hostile Western circles will 
go along with that evaluation. At the United Nations, 
'Abd-al-Amir al-Anbari did a wonderful job that few, in his 
place, could match. The same could be said for 'Abd-al-Razzaq 
al-Hashimi, who steered a successful media effort from Paris 
under unfavorable circumstances and an unequal balance of forces. 
  Even Henry Kissinger, renowned for his feats on the 
diplomatic battlefront, could not have outperformed Tariq 'Aziz, 
Nizar Hamdun, or al-Sahhaf. The diplomatic team of any nation 
with circumstances similar to those of Iraq would probably do no 
better. 
  In the kind of circumstances -- a bottleneck -- Iraq is 
going 
through, such brilliant diplomats should be retained, not fired. 
Iraq has had more than its share of exhaustion and bloodletting 
over the last three decades. 
  It is more than likely that BABIL's admonitions to the 
directors of Iraq's foreign policy are not inspired by the 
country's top leadership, but are the opinion of their authors. 
If, indeed, they are inspired from above, then Iraq is in for a 
big loss that it can ill afford in these particularly hard and 
critical times. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-11646 </DOCNO>
