<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   G-15 Summit Closing Sessions Held in New Delhi </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    G-15 Summit Closing Sessions Held in New Delhi </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    GATT Meeting, Wage Issue Reviewed </H4>

<F P=102> BK3003140794 Kuala Lumpur Radio Malaysia Network in English 
1300 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK3003140794 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur Radio Malaysia Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Group of 15 developing countries, or G-15, will 
take a common position to ensure that interests of South 
countries are protected and informed at the GATT ministerial 
meeting in Marrakesh, Morocco next month. This is agreed upon 
by leaders attending the fourth G-15 summit in New Delhi, India. 
Briefing Malaysian journalists, Foreign Affairs Minister Datuk 
Abdullah Ahmad Badawi said the leaders agreed that ministers 
representing the group at Marrakesh should meet before the 
meeting to coordinate their positions. 
  He said the subject on the need to impose a global minimum 
wage raised by Prime Minister Datuk Sri Dr. Mahathir will be 
viewed with concern. Efforts should be made to ensure such a 
move is not approved or endorsed. If a global minimum wage is 
imposed, it will have serious negative consequences in the 
industries and economies of the South countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-11649 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes062yy_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-062 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  31 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   G-15 Summit Closing Sessions Held in New Delhi </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    G-15 Summit Closing Sessions Held in New Delhi </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Mahathir on Marrakesh Declaration </H4>

<F P=102> BK3103092694 Kuala Lumpur Voice of Malaysia in English 0800 
GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK3103092694 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur Voice of Malaysia </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Datuk Sri Dr. Mahathir Mohamed says countries of 
the South can meet the challenge of the so-called social clause 
to be included in the Marrakesh Declaration if they stand 
together. 
  The United States proposes to include Marrakesh Ministerial 
Declaration, the clause of seeking a committment to address the 
link between social and labor standards towards international 
trade in the world trade organization. 
  The prime minister said this when replying to a question 
posed to him at the news conference at the end of the fourth 
G-15 summit in New Delhi. He said if the U.S. and other 
developed nations insist on imposing a global minimum wage, it 
will not be advantageous to the South nations. He pointed out 
that cheap labor is the only comparative advantage the 
developing world has against the developed nations. The 
developed countries on the other hand, have full advantages, 
namely, capital, technological knowhow, management and marketing 
know-how, and huge domestic markets. 

</TEXT>

