<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cairo Talks Stall, Resume; Agreement Announced </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cairo Talks Stall, Resume; Agreement Announced </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Delegations Resume Discussions </H4>

<F P=102> NC3003171494 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1705 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC3003171494 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 30 Mar (MENA)--The Palestinian and Israeli 
delegations led by Nabil Sha'th and Amnon Shahaq resumed their 
negotiations here this evening. 
  A Palestinian source has told MENA that the two sides will 
discuss how to reach an agreement on the security arrangements 
and international protection in Hebron in accordance with 
Security Council Resolution 904. They will also discuss the 
possibility of extending these arrangements to the Gaza Strip in 
view of the deteriorating situation there after the killing of 
six Palestinians in Gaza two days ago. 
  In its statement to MENA, the Palestinian source noted that 
the two sides have not yet reached an agreement on the security 
arrangements, adding that the negotiations are still going on in 
this regard. 
  A Palestinian-Israeli subcommittee met all night last night 
to discuss the volatile situation in the occupied territories. 
The negotiators referred the outcome of their discussion 
concerning these arrangements and international protection in 
Hebron and Gaza Strip to the Palestinian leadership in Tunis and 
the Israeli Government as part of the continued consultations. 
  MENA has learned from sources close to the negotiations that 
the two delegations have met only when the green light has been 
received from Tunis. 
  Israeli sources said that Israel has approved of the 
presence 
of 100 members of the Palestinian police force and 70 
international observers armed with light weapons in Hebron. 
However, Palestinian sources say the Palestinian delegation has 
rejected the Israeli proposal. 

</TEXT>

