<H3> <TI>   Cairo Talks Stall, Resume; Agreement Announced </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cairo Talks Stall, Resume; Agreement Announced </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Hebron Security Agreement Announced </H4>

<F P=102> NC3103052694 Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network in 
Arabic 0500 GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC3103052694 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Dr. Nabil Sha'th, head of the Palestinian delegation 
to the peace talks, has stated that the Palestinian and Israeli 
delegations have agreed on the security arrangements in the city 
of Hebron in the occupied West Bank. Dr. Sha'th pointed out 
that there will be an international presence in Hebron but no 
Palestinian police will be deployed in the city. He added that 
the two delegations, in meetings lasting until early this 
morning, agreed to resume talks on the withdrawal from Gaza and 
Jericho. Dr. Sha'th noted that details of the agreement will 
be announced this morning. 
  [In a related report, Paris AFP in English at 2339 GMT on 30 
March adds the following: "Israel and the Palestine Liberation 
Organisation will sign an agreement on security in the West Bank 
town of Hebron here at 10 a.m. (0800 GMT) Thursday, PLO 
negotiator Nabil Sha'th said. 
  ["He said the conclusion of an agreement would be announced 
simultaneously in Jerusalem and the PLO headquarters of Tunis. 
  ["A reliable Palestinian source said that under the accord 
the number of international observers in Hebron, where a Jewish 
settler massacred 30 Arab worshippers in a mosque on February 
25, would be raised to 150. 
  ["But no Palestinian policemen would be deployed in the 
town, 
the source added. 
  ["The observers would come from Norway, Denmark and another 
western European country."] 

</TEXT>

