<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commentary Examines Expanding Ties With Kuwait </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Commentary Examines Expanding Ties With Kuwait </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2903182194 Tehran IRIB Television First Program Network in 
Persian 1657 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2903182194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRIB Television First Program Network </F>
<F P=105>  Persian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Station commentary] </F>
  [Excerpts] In his meeting yesterday with Kuwaiti Amir 
Shaykh Jabir al-Ahmad al-Sabah, our country's Roads and 
Transport Minister Akbar Torkan submitted to him a message from 
Mr. Hashemi-Rafsanjani, president of the Islamic Republic of 
Iran. Although the content of the president's message has not 
been publicized, according to informed sources, the message was 
chiefly in connection with friendly ties and cooperation between 
Iran and Kuwait. 
  Our country's roads and transport minister, who started his 
three-day visit by meeting the amir of Kuwait, has also met the 
Kuwaiti prime minister and has conferred with him about the 
expansion of bilateral cooperation in economic and political 
spheres. 
  In this visit, Mr. Torkan will sign a maritime agreement 
between the two countries. The first shipping line between the 
two countries has been operating actively since February last 
year. The opening of an active shipping line between the two 
countries is in reality a new chapter in the process of 
consolidating economic and political bonds between the two 
Muslim and fraternal nations of Iran and Kuwait. In addition, 
the distinguished and unique geopolitical situation of Iran has 
made our country a major communications link between Muslim 
countries, in particular as Iran links Arab countries -- 
especially Persian Gulf littoral states -- to the newly 
independent Muslim countries of Central Asia. 
  The expansion of cordial and fraternal ties between Iran and 
Kuwait is taking place at a time when there are vigorous 
attempts by a number of Western countries and their allies in 
the region to mar Iran's relations with its southern neighbors. 
However, the present state of relations shows that despite the 
wish of the enemies and their extensive political and propaganda 
endeavours aimed at creating distance between Iran and its 
neighbors, the present realities in the region prove that there 
exist many profound bonds, as well as common interests and 
objectives, the attainment of which is dependent upon the 
expansion of cordial relations between historical neighbors in 
the region. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

