<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peres `Seriously Considering' Early Gaza Withdrawal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Peres `Seriously Considering' Early Gaza Withdrawal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA3003193894 Jerusalem New Channel 2 Television Network in 
Hebrew 1800 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA3003193894 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem New Channel 2 Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres by political </F>
correspondent 'Imanu'el Rosen at the Foreign Ministry in 
Jerusalem on 30 March -- recorded] 
  [Text] Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres this evening 
commented on the negotiations with the Palestinians. He said 
that Israel was now seriously considering implementing an early 
withdrawal from the Gaza Strip even before the negotiations were 
fully completed. Our political correspondent 'Imanu'el Rosen 
interviewed the foreign minister a short while ago. 
  [Begin recording] [Peres] I think that both sides want to 
extricate themselves from this confusing situation and achieve 
results. The time is ripe for decisions and an interim period 
may only invite further trouble. 
  [Rosen] Sir, you are about to send armed Palestinian 
policemen and an multinational force into the powder keg that is 
Hebron. When will the government finally make the decision it 
is constantly discussing and inching toward to evacuate some of 
the Jewish settlers from Hebron? 
  [Peres] First of all, I would like to make things perfectly 
clear. The Jewish residents of Hebron are not in charge of the 
Cave of the Patriarchs. The Israeli Government, through the IDF 
[Israel Defense Forces], is responsible for the Cave of 
Patriarchs and for guaranteeing freedom of access and worship at 
the site. As for Jewish settlers residing in Hebron, the 
government has to reach a decision. There is no point in 
ministers, including myself, making premature statements. The 
appropriate place for discussions is in the cabinet, not the 
media. Clearly, we are facing a very difficult problem. It is 
not a problem of rights but a problem of relations. 
  [Rosen] Is Israel ready to consider starting its withdrawal 
from the Gaza Strip even before the negotiations are completed 
in order to meet the target date of 13 April? 
  [Peres] I believe that any reasonable proposal will be 
examined on an individual basis. I do not want to make any 
generalizations, but the Palestinians are not the only ones who 
want to enter the Gaza Strip quickly. We also want to transfer 
authority to them quickly. There is no point in gaining another 
week or two of riots. We have no interest in this. All the 
violent confrontations which took place recently cause all of us 
pain, and we have no interest in seeing any further bloodshed, 
not of Arabs and certainly not of Jews. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

