<H3> <TI>   Kakh Members Seeking Deportation to South Lebanon </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kakh Members Seeking Deportation to South Lebanon </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA3003195394 Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1800 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA3003195394 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1800 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=105> Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Five members of the Kakh organization, settlers from 
the territories who are under administrative detention, have 
asked the prime minister to deport them to south Lebanon, an 
area they consider the birthright of the tribe of Asher, one of 
the 12 biblical tribes of Israel. 
  Our army affairs correspondent Alon Ben-David reports that 
the five men claim that their appeal was neither a media gimmick 
or a joke. They assert that their deportation to south Lebanon 
would satisfy the prime minister's craving to be rid of them and 
also get them out of jail. The five said that in south Lebanon 
they could contribute to the conquest of Eretz Yisra'el and the 
war against terrorism while realizing their Jewish and Zionist 
aspirations. 

