<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prime Minister Interviewed on Various Bilateral Relations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Prime Minister Interviewed on Various Bilateral Relations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK3103091694 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 0830 
GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK3103091694 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The prime minister has expressed the hope that 
enhanced cooperation between India and the United States will 
continue despite sharp differences in some areas of national 
importance. In an interview published in the latest issue of 
INDIA NEWS, Mr. Narasimha Rao described Indo-U.S. relations as 
multifaceted, complex, and replete with challenges and 
opportunities. He said U.S. is India's largest trading partner 
as well as the largest source of foreign direct investment. 
  Referring to China, Mr. Rao said there has been steady 
improvement in Sino-Indian relations over the last few years. 
The uptrend in ties has facilitated attempts to resolve the 
difficult boundary question between the two countries. 

</TEXT>

