<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   'Arafat Meets Ambassadors on Jabalyah Killings </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    'Arafat Meets Ambassadors on Jabalyah Killings </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Receives Several Western Envoys </H4>

<F P=102> JN3003201294 Baghdad Voice of the PLO in Arabic 1700 GMT 30 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN3003201294 </F>
<F P=104>  Baghdad Voice of the PLO </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] During meetings with several Western ambassadors at 
the PLO headquarters in the Tunisian capital, brother leader 
President Abu-'Ammar [Yasir 'Arafat] stressed the need to ensure 
international protection for the Palestinians of the occupied 
territories. He underscored the role Europe can play to ensure 
this protection. These remarks were made in the aftermath of 
the martyrdom of six Fatah heroes in the Jabalyah camp the day 
before yesterday, Monday, at the hands of the terrorist 
undercover units affiliated with the Israeli Army. 
  Brother President Abu-'Ammar also underlined the need to 
implement UN Security Council Resolution 904, which provides for 
international protection for the Palestinian people. He held 
the United States and Russia, cosponsors of the peace process, 
responsible for providing this protection. 
  Brother leader President Abu-'Ammar described the 
assassination of the six Fatah heroes in the Jabalyah camp as a 
new massacre. He added: In this regard, the first possibility 
that comes to mind is that Rabin might have been well aware of 
the plans to commit these massacres. He might have chosen to 
condone them. The second possibility is that these massacres 
were committed by Israeli Army units without Rabin's prior 
knowledge. One can derive no comfort from either possibility. 
This has grave repercussions on the entire peace process, he 
maintained. 

</TEXT>

