<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-063 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  31 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Inter-Arab Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Western Envoys Briefed on Arab Support for Libya </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Western Envoys Briefed on Arab Support for Libya </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC3103163094 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1300 GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC3103163094 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 31 Mar (MENA)--Arab League Secretary General 
Dr. 'Ismat 'Abd-al-Majid met today with French Ambassador to 
Cairo Patrick LeClercq, British Ambassador Christopher Long, and 
U.S. Charge d'Affaires David Hill. 
  Dr. 'Abd-al-Majid briefed the three envoys on the Arab 
League 
Council resolution from its recent meeting to support the Libyan 
stand in the Western-Libyan Lockerbie crisis and the Council's 
adoption of a proposal to try the two suspected Libyan nationals 
before the International Court of Justice in The Hague. 
  Dr. 'Abd-al-Majid said after the meeting that Libya took a 
flexible stand when it agreed to the trial of its suspected 
citizens before a neutral body. He said that the proposal 
adopted by the Arab League Council at its recent meeting calls 
for the travel of a Scottish court and judges to The Hague 
because the U.S. plane crashed over the Scottish town of 
Lockerbie and the law to apply in such a case is that of the 
country where the incident happened. 
  The Arab League chief said that Scottish law is more 
flexible 
than English law, which only stipulates two outcomes of a trial: 
either guilty or not guilty. 
  He added that he proposed at the meeting to have the 
Security 
Council issue a resolution transferring the Scottish court to 
The Hague in order to begin the trial of the Libyans suspected 
of involvement in the Lockerbie case. 
  He stressed that Libya is responsive and eager not to 
escalate the Libyan-Western crisis since such an escalation will 
have grave consequences for Libya, the neighboring countries, 
the Mediterranean Sea countries, and even the European 
countries, which will not be happy with the imposition of an 
embargo on the export of Libyan oil. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-11744 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes063bb_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-063 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  31 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Inter-Arab Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   'Abd-al-Majid, Libya's al-Bishari Discuss Lockerbie </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    'Abd-al-Majid, Libya's al-Bishari Discuss Lockerbie </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC3103171994 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1450 GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC3103171994 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 31 Mar (MENA)--Arab League Secretary General 
Dr. 'Ismat 'Abd-al-Majid met today with Ibrahim al-Bishari, 
Libya's permanent representative to the Arab League. 
'Abd-al-Majid briefed al-Bishari on the outcome of his meeting 
today with the British and French ambassadors and the U.S. 
charge d'affairs in Cairo. 
  After the meeting, al-Bishari said 'Abd-al-Majid has a clear 
concept of Libya's crisis with the West. This concept is based 
on two points--safeguarding Libya's sovereignty and upholding 
international law. 
  Al-Bishari said the Arab League supports the stand of Libya, 
which does not seek to escalate the crisis so that its effects 
will not adversely affect the whole region. 
  Al-Bishari described the international blockade of his 
country as tantamount to "the illegal detention of a people 
inside a small country with limited capabilities and resources." 
He noted that it is in Libya's interest to solve the problem 
and not to enter into a showdown with three major states. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

