<DATE1>  31 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Groups Criticize Hebron Agreement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Opposition Groups Criticize Hebron Agreement </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    PFLP-GC: Prelude to `Civil War' </H4>

<F P=102> JN3103204294 (Clandestine) Al-Quds Palestinian Arab Radio in 
Arabic 1730 GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN3103204294 </F>
<F P=104>  (Clandestine) Al-Quds Palestinian Arab Radio </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] An official spokesman for the Popular Front for the 
Liberation of Palestine-General Command [PFLP-GC] has stated the 
following: 
  More than 40 days have passed since the al-Ibrahimi Mosque 
massacre. Press statements and angry announcements have been 
made and threats issued to stop the negotiations unless the 
Zionist enemy submits to the demands of the so-called 
Palestinian negotiating delegation and its leadership. There 
was also a period of stalling, procrastination, and threats to 
use the veto. Yet all this, including the PLO leadership in 
Tunis and Resolution No. 904, only affirmed one unchanging fact; 
namely, that Palestinian blood was exploited in the auctions and 
markets of [the Middle East] settlement both in Washington and 
the Camp David capital to orchestrate the political process. 
'Arafat never fails to provide evidence of his direct and 
indirect involvement in underrating the blood of our Palestinian 
people, coordinating his positions with those who want from the 
settlement the liquidation of our cause and to conspire against 
our people and their objectives. 
  'Arafat's most recent Cairo accord--calling for deploying a 
multinational force--confirms the anticipated results of the 
maneuvers of this treasonous leadership that had issued 
deceptive statements on the status of the Hebron settlers, 
raised the prospect of suspending the talks unless they were 
evicted, and then demanded that the future of Jerusalem and the 
settlements be put on the agenda before the expiration of the 
first phase of self-rule. 
  However, the latest Cairo accord is evidence of how lightly 
our people are being taken, along with their memory and 
principles. We in the PFLP-GC view this accord as a transparent 
attempt to betray the blood of the Hebron massacre martyrs and 
our people's cause. We ask whether a token force made up of 
only dozens of blue helmets and operating under a limited 
timeframe and the control of the enemy and the Hebron town 
council can provide our people with real protection in the face 
of the terror of the settlers and the enemy military. 
  This accord reinforces the settlements and runs counter to 
the fiery statements made by 'Arafat in the aftermath of the 
massacre. The token international force is just another false 
witness. 
  The PFLP-GC's official spokesman adds: In the latest Cairo 
accord, 'Arafat brushed aside the Arab refusal to return to the 
negotiating table while the Zionist terror persists. In the 
final analysis, the return to the negotiations accommodates a 
U.S.-Zionist decision and shows 'Arafat cannot wait to complete 
the self-rule conspiracy. Talk about deploying a 'Arafatist 
police force by mid-April within the framework of self-rule 
arrangements is like throwing sand in ones eyes and a prelude to 
civil war being programmed by the parties to the conspiracy and 
executed by 'Arafat and his lieutenants. 
  The spokesman concludes: We have absolute faith in our 
people's awareness and capacity to thwart what is being hatched 
against them. Our people's will and their mujahidin are sure to 
thwart all the maneuvers, whose authors will reap only disgrace. 
Revolution until the liberation of land and man. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-11762 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes063dd_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-063 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  1 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Groups Criticize Hebron Agreement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Opposition Groups Criticize Hebron Agreement </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    DFLP, Islamic Jihad React </H4>

<F P=102> JN0104142294 Paris Radio Monte Carlo in Arabic 1200 GMT 1 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0104142294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio Monte Carlo </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Palestinian opposition has condemned the 
PLO-Israeli agreement on Hebron security and asked the 
Palestinian police force, which will be deployed in the 
autonomous region, not to thwart attacks aimed at the Israeli 
occupation. 
  The Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine [DFLP] 
has denounced what it called the observers deal in Hebron and 
regarding it as an ineffectual deal confined to the presence of 
a limited number of European observers with no security powers 
and without any deterrent measures against the settlers and 
settlements. It also considered this a new concession in the 
'Arafat leadership's long line of concessions under the pressure 
and blackmail of the United States and Israel. 
  Those who speak on behalf of the ten Palestinian factions 
opposed to the Oslo agreement say that the measures which have 
been agreed on in Hebron will not prevent new massacres of 
Palestinians. Fathi al-Shaqaqi, secretary general of the 
Islamic Jihad Organization, says that yesterday's agreement in 
Cairo does not ensure for the Palestinians a minimum level of 
security and the international presence is useless because the 
international observers will not play the role of policemen. He 
said the Islamic Jihad will continue against the Zionists in all 
parts of occupied Palestine and asked the Palestinian police 
personnel not to hinder his organization's operations against 
the Israeli enemy, as he put it. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-11763 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes063dd_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-063 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  31 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Groups Criticize Hebron Agreement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Opposition Groups Criticize Hebron Agreement </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    PFLP, Other Figures Reject Accord </H4>

<F P=102> JN3103165894 Paris Radio Monte Carlo in Arabic 1200 GMT 31 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN3103165894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio Monte Carlo </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Dawud Talhami, the spokesman of the Democratic 
Front for the Liberation of Palestine has described the 
agreement on Hebron security as a submission to Israel's stands 
and terms. The agreement did not tackle the presence of 
settlers in Hebron, maintained the Qiryat Arba' settlement, and 
has not put an end to settler terrorism, he added. The new 
agreement watered down the international protection and confined 
it to 160 observers, Talhami said. 
  The signing of the agreement on the international presence 
in 
Hebron will allow the resumption of the autonomy negotiations 
next Monday [4 April], according to PLO ambassador to Jordan, 
al-Tayyib 'Abd-al-Rahim, who announced that the first units of 
the Palestinian force will begin deployment in Gaza and Jericho 
the next day and will complete deployment on 13 April. As for 
the Israeli forces, they will redeploy in these areas. Our 
correspondent Basim Abu- Sumayyah informs us of the general 
conditions in the occupied Palestinian territories: 
  [Begin recording] Israeli military officials have said the 
Israeli Army is prepared to withdraw from Gaza and Jericho and 
redeploy within 72 hours of receiving orders. [passage omitted] 
Former Hebron Mayor Mustafa al-Natshah, who is expected to 
return to his post shortly, has welcomed the deployment of the 
international forces in the town, regarding it as a good step if 
the members of this force are capable of providing genuine 
protection for the Palestinians. He emphasized the need to 
disarm and evacuate the settlers to provide security and 
stability for the Palestinians. 
  On the other hand, supporters of the Popular Front for the 
Liberation of Palestine [PFLP] have rejected the agreement, 
which fails to provide genuine protection for the Palestinian 
people. 'Abd-al-'Alim Da'nah said that what is required is an 
opportunity for a just peace and not reaching a truce between 
the victim and the perpetrator. 
  Islamic law judge al-Shaykh Tayseer al-Tamimi expressed fear 
that the deployment of the international force will help 
consecrate the partition of the town which was imposed by the 
Israeli forces. [passage omitted] [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

