<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rabin, Peres, Others React to Hebron Agreement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rabin, Peres, Others React to Hebron Agreement </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Sources Voice `Mixed Feelings' </H4>

<F P=102> TA3103191794 Jerusalem New Channel 2 Television Network in 
Hebrew 1800 GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA3103191794 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem New Channel 2 Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Video report by political correspondent 'Imanu'el Rosen] </F>
  [Excerpts] Sources in Jerusalem are concerned that the 
entrance of the international force into Hebron will create 
difficulties, but Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin this evening said 
he hopes this is an exceptional and one-time arrangement. Our 
political correspondent 'Imanu'el Rosen heard the Israeli 
reaction to the Cairo agreement: 
  [Rosen] In Jerusalem there are mixed feelings today. On the 
one hand there is satisfaction with the success in defusing the 
dangerous Hebron situation; on the other hand there is concern 
about the precedent and difficulties involved in bringing 
international forces into the territories. [passage omitted] 
  The PLO gains three things from the international presence: 
international recognition in the special problems of Hebron; 
interference with Israeli activities in the city; and receiving 
something that Israel sharply opposed from the beginning. The 
PLO also received a promise to accelerate the withdrawal process 
from the Gaza Strip. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

