<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials, Media Comment on Blockade of al-'Aqabah </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Officials, Media Comment on Blockade of al-'Aqabah </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Paper Sees Talks Linkage </H4>

<F P=102> JN0104073294 Amman SAWT AL-SHA'B in Arabic 1 Apr 94 pp 1, 14 </F>
<F P=103> JN0104073294 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman SAWT AL-SHA'B </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Editorial: "Will Washington Lift The Siege on Jordan </F>
During April?"] 
  [Text] Since the negotiations on the Jordanian and other 
tracks are scheduled to resume in April, the U.S. Administration 
must reconsider its siege of Jordan. This is especially true 
because His Majesty King Husayn linked Jordan's participation in 
the negotiations with the lifting of the siege imposed on the 
Port of al-'Aqabah. 
  It is true that President Bill Clinton yesterday affirmed 
that the negotiations on the Jordanian, Syrian, and Lebanese 
tracks will resume in April as scheduled. However, it is also 
true that the continuation of the U.S. siege of the Port of 
al-'Aqabah will obstruct the resumption of the negotiations on 
the Jordanian track. 
  U.S. Secretary of State Christopher promised to take 
measures 
to assist Jordan in facing the siege. However, the U.S. stand 
on the siege has yet to change. This U.S. stand needs to be 
seriously reconsidered in a way that is in keeping with Jordan's 
seriousness about stopping negotiations if the siege continues. 
In other words, the U.S. Administration should respect Jordan's 
interests and stop trying to harm its economy and trade by 
continuing the unjust siege. The U.S. Administration should 
realize that Jordan will not submit to unjustified pressures and 
harassments. 
  The U.S. Administration should review its recent stand on 
the 
identity of Jerusalem and should not disavow its Arabism. It 
should appreciate His Majesty King Husayn's historic concern 
about the Arabism of Jerusalem. This is especially so since all 
the Security Council resolutions on which the peace process is 
based stipulate that Jerusalem is an integral part of the 
occupied Arab territories. 
  Moreover, Israel's decision to annex Arab Jerusalem is 
unrecognized by legitimate international bodies, leb by the 
Security Council itself. 
  The U.S. Administration is fully aware of the burdens Jordan 
has been shouldering as a result of the Gulf crisis and the 
serious economic and social losses it has been suffering on all 
levels. 
  However, instead of compensating Jordan for its large 
losses, 
the U.S. Administration continued the siege, with the intention 
of causing more harm to its economy and trade. The U.S. 
Administration is doing this in an attempt to force Jordan to 
abandon the constants of its principled stands. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-11805 </DOCNO>
