<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   PLO: Israel Takes `First Step' With Hebron Accord </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PLO: Israel Takes `First Step' With Hebron Accord </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC3103184494 Paris AFP in English 1758 GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC3103184494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tunis, March 31 (AFP) -- Israel has taken the first 
step toward protecting Palestinians by signing an accord with 
the PLO Thursday [31 March] to deploy 160 foreign observers in 
the West Bank town of Hebron, a PLO spokesman said. 
  The accord signed in Cairo was "a first step in applying 
(UN) 
Security Council Resolution 904," the spokesman said. 
  The resolution, adopted on March 18, condemned the massacre 
of 30 Palestinians by a Jewish settler at a Hebron mosque on 
February 25 and called for international protection for the 
Palestinians in the occupied territories. 
  The PLO spokesman, quoted by the official WAFA news agency, 
welcomed the participation of "friendly countries in the 
international force" which is to deploy in the West Bank town. 
  But he urged additional measures "to guarantee effective 
international protection for the Palestinian people, its land 
and its holy sites." 
  He called on Israel to fulfill all the conditions necessary 
to ensure the observers could complete their neutral mission and 
said the PLO was "ready to help them in the task." 
  Other problems still to be resolved included settlers 
carrying arms and "the presence of extremist settlers and their 
terrorist activities," he said. 
  The PLO would continue its efforts to protect all 
Palestinians and "wipe out centres of terrorism," as well as 
pushing ahead with deployment of a Palestinian security force in 
the Gaza Strip and Jericho as set out in the Declaration of 
Principles signed in Washington in September. 
  Talks on launching Palestinian self-rule resumed Thursday 
after the security deal was signed in Cairo. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-11821 </DOCNO>
